<div id="review_2868841766" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2868841766" />
    <a title="Christy Hall" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/70403819-christy-hall"><img alt="Christy Hall" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1564339262p2/70403819.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2868841766?book_show_action=true">Jan 16, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Christy Hall" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Christy Hall" href="/user/show/70403819-christy-hall">Christy Hall</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/70403819-christy-hall?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/70403819-christy-hall?shelf=magical-realism">magical-realism</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
                  <em>
                    This review has been hidden because it contains spoilers. To view it,
                    <a href="#" onclick="Effect.toggle(&#39;reviewTextContainer2868841766&#39;); return false;">click here.</a>
                  </em>
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2868841766" class="readable"
                    style="display:none"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3305787100195192343">Magical realism is an art form I love to sink into - I don’t care if it’s literature, art or film. It makes me feel heavy with understanding of the world, other people and myself. Like I can reach out with my heart and feel the universe and everything in it. It is probably my favorite genre but one I can’t read too often. It leaves me too raw. <br/><br/>Bender’s The Particular Sadness of Lemon Cake is a beautifully crafted tale about a young girl named Rose who finds on her ninth birthday that she has the</span>
  <span id="freeText3305787100195192343" style="display:none">Magical realism is an art form I love to sink into - I don’t care if it’s literature, art or film. It makes me feel heavy with understanding of the world, other people and myself. Like I can reach out with my heart and feel the universe and everything in it. It is probably my favorite genre but one I can’t read too often. It leaves me too raw. <br /><br />Bender’s The Particular Sadness of Lemon Cake is a beautifully crafted tale about a young girl named Rose who finds on her ninth birthday that she has the power to taste another person’s feelings in the food they make. As in any coming of age story, she struggles with her newfound knowledge, especially of her mother’s despair and longing. Rose learns too much about her world through her food experiences. The needy love of a girl for a boy when she makes him a sandwich. The feeling of being late and constantly behind in a cookie. The light of love in an organic turkey sandwich that makes Rose jealous of her best friend. The only way around her power - the only way for her to exist in her world - is to eat food without feelings. Processed and empty. Until she herself becomes like a factory, cold and inhuman. Rose’s journey of self-discovery, of learning to live in a world where she has a distaste for food and for those who make her feel things she doesn’t want to know, is a powerful look at how one can be at peace once we accept who we are. <br /><br />The characters make this book. While events happen, it isn’t really about the plot so much as about Rose’s discovery of others, the world and ultimately herself. Her mother, father, brother Joseph and George all help to illuminate some universal truth Rose must learn. Often, I was angry at characters who failed to take the time to figure her out. They dismiss her as sweet, kind, annoying, weird, pretty like sea glass. Rose is Coq au Vin, rich and layered. How could they dismiss her so easily? <br /><br />Rose’s mother is an empty container wanting to be filled. Or perhaps she’s more like a solar powered light, shining brightly but needing something outside of herself to recharge the batteries. She so wants to be loved and fulfilled. Her yearning leaves an ache in the soul. Rose’s father has long denied himself his purpose out of fear. He finds calm in his linear work. He wants to love, to have passion, but he’s so very afraid of what will happen if he gives in. Joseph is not made for this world. He has a unique ability, one that helps him cope with a world in which he has no place. Because they all are going through such powerful things, Rose must journey alone most of the time. George, her brother’s friend, is the only one who takes time to understand her, believes in her ability and wants her to reach her potential. He’s a beautiful character full of love and kindness. Everyone should have a George. <br /><br />The Particular Sadness of Lemon Cake made me feel sadness, joy, love, loss, anger, yearning, hope...I feel simply full of life after finishing Rose’s tale.</span>
  <a data-text-id="3305787100195192343" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


