    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_142573273" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/142573273" />
    <a title="trina" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/910324-trina"><img alt="trina" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1581483418p2/910324.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/142573273?book_show_action=true">Jan 21, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="trina" class="user" itemprop="url" name="trina" href="/user/show/910324-trina">trina</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>


          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">absolutely no one</span></div>

        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/910324-trina?shelf=over-rated-and-terrible">over-rated-and-terrible</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer142573273" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer840965587747131151">for having such a fantastic and intriguing premise, this book sure is completely godawful. being a fan of magic realism, and of &apos;like water for chocolate&apos;, another book about emotion informing food and the course of an entire family&apos;s existence, i thought for sure i&apos;d enjoy a book about a little girl who can taste people&apos;s emotions by eating the food they&apos;ve prepared and how she copes with learning her loved one&apos;s deepest secrets... i was wrong. or at least i pinned my hopes on the wrong book. i</span>
  <span id="freeText840965587747131151" style="display:none">for having such a fantastic and intriguing premise, this book sure is completely godawful. being a fan of magic realism, and of 'like water for chocolate', another book about emotion informing food and the course of an entire family's existence, i thought for sure i'd enjoy a book about a little girl who can taste people's emotions by eating the food they've prepared and how she copes with learning her loved one's deepest secrets... i was wrong. or at least i pinned my hopes on the wrong book. in someone else's hands, it might've been masterful. <br /><br />i've read so much praise of this aimee bender person, i was utterly prepared to love this book, and then it just... shit all over my expectations. her prose is overwritten, i see nothing lyrical about it. her characters are flat little convenient cliches of dysfunctional family members, and for the most part totally unlikable and unsympathetic. you'd think, with our main character being able to discern secret feelings and longings, that there'd be more character development than 'mom was sad for no apparent reason and now she's having an affair' and 'dad is very logical and distant aka a lawyer'. AND THEN to add insult to injury, there's 'my brother was a genius and then he turned into a chair.' really??? is it supposed to be allegorical? are there real people in the world who are this awkward and disconnected and totally not-human? i understand its nitpicky, when the book involves certain magical elements, to expect the characters to act according to the rules of our real world... only it's not nitpicky at all. the book takes place in the real world, only the people are utterly one-dimensional. their stupid magical 'gifts' are far more believable than their personalities (or utter lack thereof). our main character, her thoughts are never the believable thoughts of a child of eight, or thirteen, or seventeen. nor are her actions anything other than robotic and convenient and milquetoasty. AND to make matters worse, the story goes nowhere, no one learns anything, nothing is resolved... you finish this book only to wish you'd never picked it up to begin with. i read it in one sitting, knowing that if i put it down, i'd never pick it up again, hoping it would pick up, begin to go somewhere, only to be dejected and sleep deprived two hundred pages later. hats off to you, aimee bender, for getting this pap not only published but praised. you inspire me to start writing again, if only because i could probably do a better job. in my sleep.</span>
  <a data-text-id="840965587747131151" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

<tr class="no_border feedFooterReview" id="update_comment_stuff_Review142573273">
